pre: Illness (CFS), had no training the entire year.
during: Run about 2/3 and walked about 1/3 of the distance.
Low electrolyte intake caused cramping.
Around 13 gels ~200kcal (~2600kcal) each and some with caffeine.
Barely finished in time.
post: Feet blistered, barely walking, 1 month to recover just walking.
event: Lots of running by the coast so exposed to the sun and heat.
I don't recall but I think the aid stations were decent. I recall water, and maybe gels and soda.
Don't recall if there was a finishing refreshments bag but they definitely offered ice cream (magnum?).

pre: Had about 6 weeks training until health crashed for the next 6 weeks prior to event.
during: Fueled every 45m: total 5 gels ~450kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Some preworkout before and during race.
Increased electrolytes significantly helped performance.
Run almost the entire distance, but slowly with some walking at the end.
Had about 2 oranges, 2 bananas from stations, and water with juice/soda was needed too.
post: Quick partial recovery, felt ok within 1 week but need more time.
After 2 weeks I could probably attempt another event since no injuries this time but needed < 3 weeks.
event: Run through the city and some green areas which had a bit of shade and incline.
Don't recall the finishing refreshment bag but I threw away almost all of it.
takeaways: Need to increase electrolytes and gels.

pre: Mostly observed recovery from previous event so not much training, 1 1/2 marathon + misc.
Carb loaded with low quality pasta and minced beef, avoid, was constipated during race because of this type of meat.
Slept under 5h, felt heavy and unwell because of the meat but not sick, I knew the race would be difficult and sluggish.
Had preworkout before race and in drink.
Took sodium ~200g, potassium ~300g before race, added 1.5x to drink during race.
Got up at 04:30 like in Lisbon, I prefer starting at 09:00
during: Fueled every 45m, total 8 gels ~730kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Ate half a banana, half an orange during race, maybe 3 bottles of blue gatorade + water.
It was hot and sunny so I got a little sunburnt. It drained my energy and I was really slow.
Stopped to walk so many times and yet my time was faster than in Split, Croatia where I felt much better.
All the gels and extra electrolytes helped but calves started to cramp a little after 31km.
Wasted 10 minutes on 2 bathroom breaks so I could have been faster, also 2 minutes waiting after the start of the race.
Because of the heat I thought I wouldn't finish or have a much worse time.
post: Feet have some blood blisters but I can walk after the race.
event: Sunny, cloudless, exposed route mostly in underdeveloped areas.
Running some of the route by the ocean without much wind so the heat is pretty bad.
Don't recall the finishing refreshment bag but I threw away most of it.
takeaways: Don't carb load as much. Overdid it this time.

pre: For the last 2 weeks I've focused on recovery so I didn't exercise at all (although I could).
Haven't been sleeping well, taking naps during the day.
Waking up multiple times per hour the night before event so didn't sleep much but I didn't feel obviously sleep deprived.
Generally lower energy all the way up to event.
Walked < 10km day before event. Should have put on sunscreen.
Didn't overeat/carb load like last time, larger portions than regular meals but much less overall.
Had preworkout before race and in drink.
Took sodium ~200g, potassium ~300g before race, added same amount to drink for race.
Will use sunscreen and anti-chafe, especially on feet.
Running to event was difficult enough (only 2km) - CFS.
during: Fueled every 45m, total 8 gels ~860kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
Many half cups of isotonic liquid and maybe 1L of water.
Didn't have the energy because of CFS and the sun was draining despite using sunscreen.
Very slow running, waddling from side to side with a bunch of walking.
Because of CFS and the sun I started taking breaks from 18km while usually I last till around 23-24km before I need to walk a bit.
Severly dehydrated despite drinking a lot. Started mild cramping around that time till the end.
post: Feet are a little blistered, not bad, product helped a little.
Can waddle around slowly. Overall not too bad given the dehydration.
event: They started at 08:30 but staggered the runners so they made me wait for 24m before starting.
Aid stations were inconsistent and not great.
Served water, isotonic liquids and apples.
Big city, lots of people in certain areas. Clean city, good vibes.
Bunch of runners needed first aid, even just before the finish line - heatstroke?
It was hot and sunny with little shade / protection.
Best medal so far but finishing bag of refreshments was meh. Only kept the drinks.
takeaways: Need to purchase breathable, long sleeved, white top for more sun protection.
May need to increase electrolyte even more especially for sunny climates.
May need to drink more and risk toilet breaks - didn't use it once this time despite drinking a lot.
May need an additional sugary/sweet drink in case aid stations don't have any.
Carb load more, could have eaten a bit more. Was a bit hungry the day before. 500g of pasta wasn't enough.
Start to drink frequently from the start e.g. every 20m.

pre: Lots of travel to get to the island, feel kinda meh.
Kinda carb loading but with pancakes, jam, chocolate and biscuits, sodas, with a bit of regular spaghetti and meat.
Will wear sunscreen and a light colored long sleeved t-shirt. I'm unsure about the material providing sun protection because of how thin it is.
Using a new anti-chafe cream I randomly picked up at Decathlon.
Had some time to train so I run a few 10 milers and some high intensity intervals, hoping it helps.
during: Fueled every 30m, total 8 gels ~?kcal, 5 electrolyte sticks: sodium ~1200g, 250g potassium.
event: On an island, by the coast, completely exposed to the sun.
Small marathon so the chip is a thick box on the bib unlike the usual small thin line.
